To be a successful teenager, focus on doing well in school by completing assignments on time and paying attention to lectures. Start developing good habits such as setting up daily routines for studying, sleeping, and exercising.

Join extracurricular activities or clubs that interest you. This will help you develop talents and make friends with shared interests.

Be responsible about money by getting a part-time job (if permitted), managing your allowance wisely or saving for future expenses such as college tuition.

Develop strong communication skills which also includes being an active listener. Learn how to express your thoughts effectively but don't be afraid of accepting constructive criticism from others.

Respect yourself and others knowing that everyone has strengths and weaknesses. Be open-minded about other people's values, beliefs or cultures; treat everyone fairly without any prejudice.

Make health a priority by eating healthy foods, practicing personal hygiene regularly and staying physically active through exercise or sports activities that you enjoy.
